PFA: Facial expression recognition - Training Model

Project Goals:
  • Successfully detect a face
  • Successfully predict emotions from pictures by training a model
  • Generalize the predictions to live camera and build first version of final model
  • Wrap the result in an adequate python UI or compile to app
Additional functions we can add:
  • Save person's information and face
  • Show quote matching the user's emotions

Uploading Dataset¶

For the datasset, we used the one provided by kaddle on this website: https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/challenges-in-representation-learning-facial-expression-recognition-challenge/data?select=train.csv

The Data set contains 48 X 48-pixel grayscale images of the face. There are seven categories (0=Angry, 1=Disgust, 2=Fear, 3=Happy, 4=Sad, 5=Surprise, 6=Neutral)</b> present in the data. The CSV file contains two columns that are emotion that contains numeric code from 0-6 and a pixel column that includes a string surrounded in quotes for each image.

Storing Dataset¶

In [20]:
#---------------------- Spliting the DataSet------------------------------------
X_train = []      #train pixels
y_train = []      #train labels
X_test = []       #test pixels
y_test = []       #test label
for index, row in emotion_data.iterrows():    #iterate on each row and store it
    k = row['pixels'].split(" ")       #list of pixels, each pixel is an element
    try:
      if row['Usage'] == 'Training':
          X_train.append(np.array(k,'float32'))    #The desired data-type for the array is 
          y_train.append(row['emotion'])
      elif row['Usage'] == 'PublicTest':
          X_test.append(np.array(k,'float32'))
          y_test.append(row['emotion'])
    except:
      print(f"error occured at index :{index} and row:{row}")




print('----------------------- X_test')
print(X_test)
print(type(X_test))

print('----------------------- y_train')
print(y_train)
print(type(y_train))

Convert the arrays to numpy arrays so we can do several operations on it related to numpy library only like reshaping and dividing into categories Reshape the pixels arrays to be 48*48 array and each array has 1 element/pixel Convert the labels arrays into categorial ones, this function returns a matrix of binary values and have rows numbers = the input vector dimensions and have columns numbers = the number of categories

For example:

train_labels = to_categorical(train_labels, num_classes = 10)

In [21]:
#--------------------Convert Lists to Numpy arrays------------------------------
X_train = np.array(X_train, 'float32')
y_train = np.array(y_train, 'float32')
X_test = np.array(X_test,'float32')
y_test = np.array(y_test,'float32')

#-----------------------Reshape Pixels arrays---------------------------------
#normalizing data between o and 1  
X_train -= np.mean(X_train, axis=0)
X_train /= np.std(X_train, axis=0)

X_test -= np.mean(X_test, axis=0)
X_test /= np.std(X_test, axis=0)

#reshape the numpy array to be passed to the model
X_train = X_train.reshape(X_train.shape[0], 48, 48, 1)
X_test = X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0], 48, 48, 1)

print(X_test.shape)
print(type(X_test))
print(X_train.shape)

#------------------Convert Labels array to categorial ones---------------------
#y_train= tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes=7)
#y_test = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes=7)

y_train= np_utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes=7)
y_test = np_utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes=7)
print(y_train)
print(y_train.shape)
print(type(y_train))

Build CNN model¶

We will be building a specific type of CNN model which is the VGG16 (Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition) which is Convolutional Network for Classification and Detection. The model will consist of initialization of the model followed by batch normalization layer and then different convents layers with ReLu as an activation function, max pool layers, and dropouts to do learning efficiently

In [22]:
model = Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(input_shape=(X_train.shape[1:]),filters=64,kernel_size=(3,3),padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=(3,3),padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))


model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(4096, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(4096, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))  ## reduce the overfitting of the modal
model.add(Dense(7, activation='softmax')) # gives the category


model.summary()

Compile Model¶

We compile the model using Adams as optimizer,loss as categorical cross-entropy, and metrics as accuracy

In [23]:
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.0001),loss='categorical_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])

We fit the data for validation and training. Then take the batch size = 32 and epoch size = 30.

In [24]:
batch = 32
epoch = 30

# we use the fit function to train the modal. We pass the data, the data labels a batch, 
#the batch size,the epoch, verbose , the validation data (labels and pixels) and 
# the shuffle

# the modal works on batches and does its analysis and extraction thingies per batch. 
#Batch size is always a multiple of 

# we need to pass the data to the modal several times and not just once. Tha'ts the epoch
# it's the number of times in which a same data is passed to the modal

#shuffle to do some generalization to the modal and not have it overfit

# we want to reach a level in wich the training data and validation data are almost on point
history = model.fit(X_train,y_train,batch_size= batch,epochs= epoch,verbose=1,validation_data=(X_test, y_test),shuffle=True)

from IPython.display import Image, display
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg

TGREEN =  '\033[1;37;42m'
TRED =    '\033[1;37;41m'
TYELLOW = '\033[0;43m'

for i in range (0,10):
  img_directory = str(i) + '.jpg'
  img_data = tf.keras.utils.load_img(img_directory, target_size = (48, 48))   #load the image from the directory
  img_data = tf.keras.utils.img_to_array(img_data)                            #convert the image to a Numpy array
  img_data = tf.image.rgb_to_grayscale(img_data)

  #print(img_data.shape)
  #img_data = np.array(img_data, 'float32')
  #img_data.resize(48,48,1)
  #print(img_data.shape)
  img_data = np.expand_dims(img_data, axis = 0)                     #expands the array by inserting a new axis at the specified position.
  #print(img_data.shape)

  classify = model.predict(img_data)
  display(Image(img_directory,width= 150, height=150))
  #print("\n")
  max_index = np.argmax(classify[0])
  emotion_detection = ('angry', 'disgust', 'fear', 'happy', 'sad', 'surprise', 'neutral')
  emotion_prediction = emotion_detection[max_index]

  if(max_index == 3 or max_index == 5):
    print( str(max_index) + ' = ' +  emotion_prediction)
  elif(max_index == 4 or max_index == 2 or max_index == 0):
    print( str(max_index) + ' = ' +  emotion_prediction)
  else:
    print( str(max_index) + ' = ' +  emotion_prediction)
  print("\n")
  print("\n")

from IPython.display import Image, display
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg

TGREEN =  '\033[1;37;42m'
TRED =    '\033[1;37;41m'
TYELLOW = '\033[0;43m'

for i in range (0,10):
  img_directory = str(i) + '.jpg'
  img_data = tf.keras.utils.load_img(img_directory, target_size = (48, 48))   #load the image from the directory
  img_data = tf.keras.utils.img_to_array(img_data)                            #convert the image to a Numpy array
  img_data = tf.image.rgb_to_grayscale(img_data)

  #print(img_data.shape)
  #img_data = np.array(img_data, 'float32')
  #img_data.resize(48,48,1)
  #print(img_data.shape)
  img_data = np.expand_dims(img_data, axis = 0)                     #expands the array by inserting a new axis at the specified position.
  #print(img_data.shape)

  classify = model.predict(img_data)
  display(Image(img_directory,width= 150, height=150))
  #print("\n")
  max_index = np.argmax(classify[0])
  emotion_detection = ('angry', 'disgust', 'fear', 'happy', 'sad', 'surprise', 'neutral')
  emotion_prediction = emotion_detection[max_index]

  if(max_index == 3 or max_index == 5):
    print( str(max_index) + ' = ' +  emotion_prediction)
  elif(max_index == 4 or max_index == 2 or max_index == 0):
    print( str(max_index) + ' = ' +  emotion_prediction)
  else:
    print( str(max_index) + ' = ' +  emotion_prediction)
  print("\n")
  print("\n")

We notice that between model1 and model2, model1 seems to have better chances to correctly predict the emotion in a picture or guetting close to it while model2 may have an overfitting problem.

Save the model¶

We will serialize the model to JSON and save the model's weights in a hd5 file, so we can use it to make predictions directly without retraining the model everytime.

In [28]:
model_json = model.to_json()
with open("model.json", "w") as json_file:
  json_file.write(model_json)
  model.save_weights("model.h5")

print("Saved model to disk")

Saved model to disk
